The '''{{ill|Sōhō-chūen Kofun|ja|双方中円墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sōhō-chūen Kofun|qq=}}''' (そうほうちゅうえんふん) is a type of [[:en:Kofun|Kofun]] Kofun. It is characterized by a circular main mound with '''two rectangular extensions''', one on each side.

== Overview ==
Whereas '''[[:en:Zenpokoenfun|Zenpokoenfun]]''' (keyhole-shaped kofun) feature a '''single''' rectangular extension at the front of a circular main mound, the '''Sōhō-chūen Kofun''' has '''two''' such extensions, one on either side.{{Sfn|Sōhō-chūen Kofun (Sekai Daikyakka)}} These kofun are seen primarily in the early '''[[:en:Kofun period|Kofun period]]'''. 

While '''Zenpō-kōen-fun''' typically have a designated '''frontal direction''', it is unclear which side was considered the "front" in '''Sōhō-chūen Kofun'''.{{Sfn|Izumimori|1991|p=55}}

As of 2015, only '''four confirmed examples''' of Sōhō-chūen Kofun are known in Japan.{{Sfn|Inariyama Hokutan 1-gō Fun}} Among these, '''[[:en:Kushiyama Kofun|Kushiyama Kofun]]''' is notable for having '''one smaller extension''' compared to the other.{{Sfn|Sōhō-chūen Kofun (Sekai Daikyakka)}} 

Furthermore, during the '''[[:en:Yayoi period|Yayoi period]]''', certain Kofuns also exhibited '''keyhole-shaped''' or '''Sōhō-chūen-like''' structures. These early forms likely '''evolved into the standardized keyhole-shaped and Sōhō-chūen kofun''' of the Kofun period.{{Sfn|Sōhō-chūen Kofun (Sekai Daikyakka)}} 

